<?xml version='1.0' encoding='utf-8'?>
<section xml:id="sec_robot_subsystems" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Robot Subsystems</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      A robot is a complex system composed of multiple interconnected subsystems. 
      Understanding these subsystems and how they work together is essential for 
      designing, building, and programming robotic systems.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec_mechanical_structure">
    <title>Mechanical Structure and Actuation</title>
    <p>
      The <term>mechanical structure</term> provides the physical framework of the robot, 
      including the body, links, joints, and end-effectors (such as grippers or wheels).
    </p>

    <p>
      <term>Actuators</term> are the "muscles" of a robot, converting electrical energy 
      into mechanical motion. Common types include:
      <ul>
        <li><em>Electric Motors:</em> DC motors, servo motors, and stepper motors provide 
            rotational motion</li>
        <li><em>Pneumatic Actuators:</em> Use compressed air for high-force applications</li>
        <li><em>Hydraulic Actuators:</em> Use pressurized fluid for very high-force applications</li>
        <li><em>Linear Actuators:</em> Provide direct linear motion</li>
      </ul>
    </p>

    <example xml:id="example_robotic_arm">
      <title>Robotic Arm Actuators</title>
      <p>
        A typical industrial robotic arm has multiple joints, each controlled by an 
        electric motor. A 6-axis robot arm, for example, has six servo motors that 
        allow it to position and orient its end-effector (gripper or tool) in 
        three-dimensional space with great precision.
      </p>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec_sensors">
    <title>Sensors and Perception</title>
    <p>
      <term>Sensors</term> allow robots to perceive their environment and internal state. 
      They can be categorized into two main types:
    </p>

    <dl>
      <li>
        <title>Proprioceptive Sensors</title>
        <p>Measure the robot's internal state, such as:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><em>Encoders:</em> Measure joint positions and velocities</li>
          <li><em>Inertial Measurement Units (IMUs):</em> Measure acceleration and angular velocity</li>
          <li><em>Force/Torque Sensors:</em> Measure forces applied to joints or end-effectors</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>Exteroceptive Sensors</title>
        <p>Measure properties of the external environment:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><em>Cameras:</em> Provide visual information about the environment</li>
          <li><em>LIDAR:</em> Uses laser beams to measure distances and create 3D maps</li>
          <li><em>Ultrasonic Sensors:</em> Measure distance using sound waves</li>
          <li><em>Touch/Tactile Sensors:</em> Detect contact with objects</li>
          <li><em>GPS:</em> Provides outdoor location information</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </dl>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec_computation">
    <title>Computation and Processing</title>
    <p>
      The <term>computational subsystem</term> is the "brain" of the robot, responsible 
      for processing sensor data, making decisions, and generating control commands.
    </p>

    <p>
      Modern robots use various computing platforms:
      <ul>
        <li><em>Microcontrollers:</em> Low-power processors for simple, real-time control tasks</li>
        <li><em>Single-board Computers:</em> Such as Raspberry Pi or NVIDIA Jetson for 
            more complex processing</li>
        <li><em>Industrial PCs:</em> High-performance computers for demanding applications</li>
        <li><em>Specialized Hardware:</em> GPUs for vision processing, FPGAs for custom algorithms</li>
      </ul>
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec_power">
    <title>Power Supply</title>
    <p>
      The <term>power subsystem</term> provides electrical energy to all components. 
      Power requirements vary greatly depending on the robot's size and application.
    </p>

    <p>
      Common power sources include:
      <ul>
        <li><em>Batteries:</em> Lithium-ion or lithium-polymer for mobile robots</li>
        <li><em>Wall Power:</em> AC power for stationary industrial robots</li>
        <li><em>Solar Panels:</em> For long-term outdoor operation</li>
        <li><em>Fuel Cells:</em> For extended autonomous operation</li>
      </ul>
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec_communication">
    <title>Communication and Networking</title>
    <p>
      The <term>communication subsystem</term> enables the robot to exchange information 
      with other systems, including:
    </p>

    <p>
      <ul>
        <li>Wireless communication (Wi-Fi, Bluetooth, cellular) for remote control and monitoring</li>
        <li>Wired connections (Ethernet, USB) for high-bandwidth data transfer</li>
        <li>Internal communication buses (CAN, I2C, SPI) connecting subsystems</li>
        <li>Robot-to-robot communication for multi-robot coordination</li>
      </ul>
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec_integration">
    <title>System Integration</title>
    <p>
      All these subsystems must work together seamlessly. The challenge of robotics 
      is not just building each subsystem, but integrating them into a cohesive whole 
      that can:
    </p>

    <p>
      <ul>
        <li>Read sensors at appropriate rates</li>
        <li>Process data efficiently</li>
        <li>Generate timely control commands</li>
        <li>Handle failures gracefully</li>
        <li>Operate safely around humans and other objects</li>
      </ul>
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <conclusion>
    <p>
      Understanding robot subsystems provides insight into the complexity of robotic 
      systems. Each subsystem plays a critical role, and their integration is what 
      enables robots to perceive, think, and act in the world. In the next section, 
      we'll explore how these subsystems work together in the perception-planning-control 
      loop.
    </p>
  </conclusion>
</section>
